{{Infobox mountain | name = Dun Mountain | photo = Dun mountain Nelson New Zealand.jpg | elevation_m = 1129 | prominence_ref = | listing = | label_position = | location = [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]], [[New Zealand]] | range = | coordinates = | coordinates_ref = | topo = | type = | age = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }} '''Dun Mountain''' is a mountain in the Richmond Range near the city of [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]] in [[New Zealand|New Zealand's]] [[South Island]]. It is located between the catchments of the [[Pelorus River|Pelorus]], [[Roding River|Maitai]] and [[Roding River|Roding Rivers]]. The mountain is named for its brown (Dun) colour. The colour is caused by the [[ultramafic rock]] which forms the mountain. Ultramafic Rock weathers to this colour and plant growth is also stunted due to the soils high heavy metal content.<ref name="RobinsonBrooks1996">{{cite journal|last1=Robinson|first1=Brett H.|last2=Brooks|first2=Robert R.|last3=Kirkman|first3=John H.|last4=Gregg|first4=Paul E.H.|last5=Gremigni|first5=Patrizia|title=Plant‐available elements in soils and their influence on the vegetation over ultramafic ("serpentine") rocks in New Zealand|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand|volume=26|issue=4|year=1996|pages=457–468|issn=0303-6758|doi=10.1080/03014223.1996.9517520}}</ref> The ultramafic rock formed in the earth's [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] in the Permian and is now part of the [[Dun Mountain Ophiolite Belt]].
In 1859 the rock type [[dunite]] was first identifed on the mountain and named after it.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Johnston | first1 = M. R. | year = 2007 | title = Nineteenth-century observations of the Dun Mountain Ophiolite Belt, Nelson, New Zealand and trans-Tasman correlations, | url = http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/287/1/375.abstract | journal = Geological Society, London, Special Publications | volume = 287 | issue = | pages = 375–387 | doi=10.1144/sp287.27| bibcode = 2007GSLSP.287..375J }}</ref> Between 1850 and 1865 small deposits of [[chromite]] and [[copper]] were mined on the mountain leading to the building of New Zealand's [[Dun Mountain Railway|first railway]].
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== *[https://teara.govt.nz/en/1966/dun-mountain New Zealand Encyclopedia 1966: Dun Mountain] *[https://www.nelsontasman.nz/our-story/nelson-tasman-stories/dun-mountain/ Dun Mountain Trail (bike trail 2011)] *[http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-NHSJ04_03-t1-body1-d1.html History of mining on Dun Mountain (M. R. Johnston)]
