The following is a [[:Category:City timelines|timeline]] of the [[Kisangani#History|history]] of the [[List of cities in the Democratic Republic of the Congo|city]] of [[Kisangani]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]].
{{Dynamic list}}
{{TOC right}}

==Prior to 20th century==
{{History of the Democratic Republic of the Congo}}

* 1875 - Town besieged by Arabs.{{sfn|Omasombo|2005}}
* 1883 - Europeans arrive.{{sfn|Omasombo|2005}}
* 1887 - [[Tippu Tip]] becomes governor of the Stanley Falls District in the colonial [[Congo Free State]]. 
* 1899 - [[Our Lady of the Rosary Cathedral, Kisangani|Cathédrale Notre-Dame du Rosaire]] built.{{timefact|date=October 2017}}

==20th century==
* 1904 - Catholic [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kisangani|Apostolic Prefecture of Stanley Falls]] established.<ref>{{cite web |work=Chronology of Catholic Dioceses |title= Democratic Republic of the Congo |url= http://www.katolsk.no/organisasjon/verden/chronology/congo_kinshasa |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oslo]] |location=Norway |accessdate= 22 October 2017 }}</ref>
* 1906 - [[Ponthiérville]]-Stanleyville {{illm|Kisangani-Ubundu Railway|fr|Chemin de fer Kisangani-Ubundu|lt=railway}} begins operating.{{sfn|MacGaffey|1987}}
* 1908 - Town becomes part of the colonial [[Belgian Congo]].
* 1913 - Justin Malfeyt becomes governor of Orientale Province.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stanleyville.be/gouverneurs.html |title=Liste des gouverneurs de la Province Orientale |work= Stanleyville.be |publisher=Jean-Luc Ernst |language=fr |accessdate= 23 October 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.kaowarsom.be/documents/bbom/Tome_III/Malfeyt.Justin_Prudent_Francois_Marie.pdf |year=1952 |title=Malfeyt |work={{illm|Biographie Belge d'Outre-Mer|nl|Belgische Koloniale Biografie}} |language=fr |publisher=[[Institut Royal Colonial Belge]] }} {{free access}}</ref>
* 1921 - [[Ligne Aérienne du Roi Albert]] (Leopoldville-Stanleville) airline begins operating.
* 1930 - October: Tornado occurs.<ref>{{citation |title=L'Illustration Congolaise |location=Brussels |oclc=47785474 |language=fr |year= 1931 }}</ref>
* 1935 - Town becomes seat of the newly formed Stanleyville province.<ref name=McFarland1999>{{cite book|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998 |author= Gwillim Law |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|year=1999|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |location=US |isbn=0786407298 |chapter=Democratic Republic of the Congo |pages=92-94 }}</ref>
* 1947 - Town becomes seat of the Orientale Province.<ref name=McFarland1999 />
* 1955 - [[AS Nika]] (football club) formed.
* 1957 - [[Bralima Brewery]] plant begins operating.
* 1959 - Population: 126,533 (estimate).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1960_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1965 |year=1966 |publisher=[[Statistical Office of the United Nations]] |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=140-161 |quote=Stanleyville }}</ref>
* 1960
** 30 June: City becomes part of newly independent [[Republic of the Congo (Léopoldville)|Republic of the Congo]].
** July: Unrest.<ref>{{citation |work=New York Times |date=28 June 1970 |title=Thriving Stanleyville Now Depressed Kisangani |url =https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/28/archives/thriving-stanleyville-now-depressed-kisangani.html }}</ref>{{timefact|date=October 2017}}
* 1964
** City taken by rebels during the [[Simba rebellion]].
** November: {{illm|1964 Stanleyville massacre|nl|Moordpartij Stanleystad 1964}} occurs.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/28/28-more-white-hostages-found-slain-in-stanleyville.html |work=New York Times |title= 28 More White Hostages Found Slain in Stanleyville |date=28 November 1964 }}</ref>
** Stanleyville becomes capital of the newly created [[People's Republic of the Congo]].<ref name=Emizet2016>{{cite book|author=Emizet Francois Kisangani |title=Historical Dictionary of the Democratic Republic of the Congo |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sj9mDQAAQBAJ |edition=4th |year= 2016 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield ]] |isbn= 9781442273160 }}</ref>
* 1966
** July: [[Stanleyville mutinies|Mercenaries' Mutiny]] attempted.
** Stanleyville renamed "Kisangani."<ref name=McFarland1999 />
* 1967 - Second [[Stanleyville mutinies|Mercenaries' Mutiny]] occurs.
* 1970
** Belgian king [[Baudouin of Belgium|Baudouin]] visits city.{{cn|date=October 2017}}
** Population: 216,526.{{sfn|Omasombo|2005}}
* 1971
** Société Textile de Kisangani (manufactory) begins operating.<ref name=Fute>{{cite web |work=[[Petit Futé]] |title=R.D. Congo: Kisangani |url=https://www.petitfute.com/v46953-kisangani/ |accessdate = 23 October 2017 |language=fr }}</ref>
** City becomes seat of [[Orientale Province|Haut-Zaïre]] province.<ref name=Emizet2016 />
* 1975 - Population: 297,888 (estimate).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1980_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1980 |year= |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=225-252 }}</ref>
* 1980 - May: Catholic pope [[List of pastoral visits of Pope John Paul II outside Italy|visits]] Kisangani.
* 1981 - [[University of Kisangani]] established.
* 1984 - Population: 317,581.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2000.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 2000 |year= |publisher=[[United Nations Statistics Division]] |title= Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 1986 - "Diamond deposits...first discovered."{{sfn|Omasombo|2005}}
* 1991 - September: City "pillaged...by rampaging soldiers."{{sfn|French|1997}}
* 1992 - November: Riverboat shutdown begins.<ref name=Noble1993>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/03/18/world/kisangani-journal-with-artery-severed-heart-of-africa-grows-still.html |work=New York Times |title=Kisangani Journal; With Artery Severed, Heart of Africa Grows Still |date=18 March 1993 |author=Kenneth B. Noble }}</ref>
* 1993 - December: City again looted by soldiers.<ref name=Noble1993 />
* 1994 - Population: 417,517.{{sfn|Omasombo|2005}}<ref>{{citation |year=2003 |title=Association pour le Developpement de l'Information Environmentale }}</ref>
* 1996 - November: City besieged by "Zairian soldiers fleeing the war zone" during the [[First Congo War]].{{sfn|French|1997}}
* 1997
** March: City taken by rebel forces.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/15/world/zaire-rebels-begin-attack-on-key-city-of-kisangani.html |title=Zaire Rebels Begin Attack On Key City of Kisangani |work=New York Times |date=15 March 1997 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/17/world/a-fallen-city-seeking-peace-greets-rebels.html |title= A Fallen City, Seeking Peace, Greets Rebels |author=[[James C. McKinley Jr.]] |work=New York Times |date=17 March 1997 }}</ref>
** City becomes seat of [[Orientale Province|Haut-Congo]] province.<ref name=McFarland1999 />
* 2000 - June: Rwanda-Uganda armed conflict occurs in Kisangani.<ref>{{citation |work=[[The Economist]] |location=London |url=http://www.economist.com/node/82153 |title=Congo’s hidden war |date= 15 June 2000 }}</ref>

==21st century==
* 2002 - 14-15 May: Massacre.[http://www.economist.com/node/1213296]
* 2003 - August: Arrival via Congo river of "first commercial delivery from the capital since the fighting began in 1998."<ref>{{citation |work=The Economist |location=London |url=http://www.economist.com/node/1978904 |title=A mend in the river |date= 7 August 2003 }}</ref>
* 2007 - {{illm|Médard Autsai Asenga|fr}} becomes provincial governor.<ref name=Belle2014 />
* 2008 - Guy Shilton Baendo Tofuli becomes mayor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stanleyville.be/maires.html |title=Liste des maires de la ville depuis 1960 |work= Stanleyville.be |publisher=Jean-Luc Ernst |language=fr |accessdate= 21 October 2017 }}</ref>
* 2010 - National military Camp Base in operation (approximate date).{{timefact|date=October 2017}}
* 2011 - 8 July: Airplane [[Hewa Bora Airways Flight 952|crash]] occurs at [[Bangoka International Airport]].
* 2013 - {{illm|Jean Bamanisa Saïdi|fr}} becomes provincial governor.<ref name=Belle2014>{{citation |title=RDC: le réveil de Kisangani, la belle endormie |work=[[Jeune Afrique]] |language=fr |url= http://www.jeuneafrique.com/37907/politique/rdc-le-r-veil-de-kisangani-la-belle-endormie/ |date=23 December 2014 }}</ref>
* 2015 - City becomes seat of [[Tshopo]] province (officially created in 2006).
* 2016 - {{illm|Jean Ilongo Tokole|fr|Jean Tokole Ilongo}} becomes governor of Tshopo province.<ref>{{citation |title=RDC: liste de nouveaux gouverneurs de province élus |language=fr |url=https://www.radiookapi.net/2016/03/26/actualite/politique/rdc-liste-de-nouveaux-gouverneurs-de-province-elus |date= 26 March 2016 |work=[[Radiookapi.net]] }}</ref>
* 2017 - Constant Lomata becomes governor of Tshopo province.<ref>{{citation |title=Constant Lomata nouveau gouverneur de la Tshopo |language=fr |url=https://www.radiookapi.net/2017/08/29/actualite/en-bref/constant-lomata-nouveau-gouverneur-de-la-tshopo |date= 29 August 2017 |work=Radiookapi.net }}</ref>

